Release Containment/Control

- Process relief valves that discharge to a flare to capture and combust process materials to
  prevent overpressure damage to equipment;
- Scrubber to neutralize hydrofluoric acid releases to the flare in the HF Alkylation Unit;
- Prevention, Detection and Mitigation (PDM) System in the HF Alkylation Unit;
- Manual and automatic valves (Emergency Isolation Valves) to permit isolation of equipment or
  process units;
- Automated Emergency Shutdown Systems (ESDs) for specific process parameters (e.g., high
  level, high temperature);
- Curbing or diking to contain liquid releases;
- Redundant equipment and instrumentation where needed (e.g., uninterruptible power supply for
  process control system, redundant firewater pumps); Water spray systems;
- Fire suppression and extinguishing systems;
- Emergency Response Team (ERT) equipment (fire trucks/response equipment e.g., spill cleanup
  equip, booms);
- Light oil storage tanks include release prevention barriers under the floors and lined
  containment dikes.

Other

- Trained emergency response personnel;
- Personal protective equipment (e.g., protective clothing, personal H2S monitors, self-contained
  breathing apparatus);
- Structurally adequate control buildings to help protect control systems and personnel in the event
  of an explosion;
- Emergency Warning Horn (evacuation or shelter-in-place).

1.6 Five-year Accident History

SPPR maintains a 5-year accident history that fulfills the requirements of the RMP rule. This history indicates a good record with respect to the prevention of accidental releases over the past 5 years. All incidents during the past 5 years were evaluated for potential reporting under the accidental release provisions
